wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116987"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116987"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/cameron-mcwhirter" itemprop="url" rel="author">Cameron McWhirter</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jan-wolfe" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jan Wolfe</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/aruna-viswanatha" itemprop="url" rel="author">Aruna Viswanatha</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sadie-gurman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sadie Gurman</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 15 日上午 1:22（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>亚特兰大——这里的一个大陪审团指控<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>、鲁迪·朱利安尼和其他特朗普盟友经营犯罪企业，试图推翻<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">乔·拜登</a>在佐治亚州的选举胜利，这是这位<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-guide-to-donald-trumps-legal-perils-b9b64891?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">前总统今年第四次被起诉</a>，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-new-charges-facing-donald-trump-and-how-he-might-defend-himself-53a2b45?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加深了他的法律责任。</a> 2024 年大选之前的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-new-charges-facing-donald-trump-and-how-he-might-defend-himself-53a2b45?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">困境</a>。</p><p> <a href="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/documents/GATRUMPINDICTMENT081423.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">起诉书中共有19人受到指控</a>，其中包括前特朗普白宫办公厅主任马克·梅多斯和法律顾问西德尼·鲍威尔。</p><p>总而言之，佐治亚州的指控指控这是一场大规模的犯罪阴谋，旨在推翻 2020 年选举结果并破坏美国民主。他们描述了据称通过电话、电子邮件和其他方式向州和联邦官员施压，要求其支持为特朗普赢得所需选票的努力，或断言他在佐治亚州和他失去的其他州都取得了胜利。</p><p>富尔顿县地方检察官法尼·威利斯(Fani Willis) <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fani-willis-the-no-nonsense-georgia-prosecutor-on-a-collision-course-with-donald-trump-600b88f8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">提出的</a>这份庞大的起诉书涵盖了特朗普在华盛顿面临的联邦案件的一些相同内容，但更详细地介绍了佐治亚州的努力，并提供了所谓阴谋的一些新内容。它指控特朗普犯有 13 项重罪，指控他在佐治亚州提出虚假选民欺诈指控，并向共和党官员施压，要求他帮助他确保该州的选举团选票。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=63AF554A-ED80-41F6-BE4D-ADF5F7ECFA84&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdonald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">前总统唐纳德·特朗普在州和联邦层面面临四项单独的起诉。 《华尔街日报》详细分析了每项起诉书及其对他 2024 年总统竞选的意义。摄影插图：赵安妮<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>威利斯的调查持续了两年多，他利用该州全面的反敲诈勒索法来描述一场精心策划的阴谋，目的是为了不顾佐治亚州选民的意愿继续掌权。拜登在 2020 年以微弱优势赢得该州。</p><p>威利斯在周一晚间的新闻发布会上表示：“被告参与了一项犯罪敲诈勒索活动，目的是推翻佐治亚州的总统选举结果。”他补充说，被告追求的是让特朗普夺取总统任期的非法目标。</p><p>她说她将寻求在未来六个月内进行审判。她要求被告在 8 月 25 日星期五之前自首。</p><p>特朗普在他的“真相社交”平台上宣布这项调查是一场政治迫害。 “他们为什么不在 2.5 年前起诉？因为他们想在我的政治竞选中期这样做，”他说。</p><p>特朗普的律师发表了一份声明，其中部分内容是：“我们期待对这份起诉书进行详细审查，这无疑与整个程序一样存在缺陷和违宪。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="896" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/a7dc45f6-d690-4f27-9034-c24e2929ee1d-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>起诉书详细列出了 161 项独立行为，称这些行为是阴谋扭转选举结果的一部分，首先是特朗普在总统选举后第二天发表的宣布胜利的演讲。它还指控该犯罪企业在乔治亚州富尔顿县以外以及其他州开展活动，包括密歇根州、亚利桑那州、宾夕法尼亚州、内华达州和新墨西哥州。</p><p>起诉书称，朱利安尼领导了包括佐治亚州在内的战场州的努力，以维持特朗普的权力。朱利安尼称这份起诉书“是对美国民主的侮辱”，并表示它“对我们的司法系统造成了永久的、不可挽回的伤害”。</p><p>咖啡县有几人被指控破坏投票机，咖啡县是一个距亚特兰大约 200 英里的乡村县。包括鲍威尔在内的这些被告被指控串谋盗窃电脑。鲍威尔曾散布虚假说法，称投票机被黑客入侵，将选票从特朗普转向了拜登。</p><p>威利斯还起诉了约翰·伊士曼和肯尼思·切斯布罗，他们在法律备忘录中辩称，时任副总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mike-pence">迈克·彭斯</a>可以阻止选举人团选票获得认证。</p><p>其他被告包括特朗普前律师珍娜·埃利斯（Jenna Ellis）和</p>特朗普政府司法部官员杰弗里·克拉克敦促他的同事根据特朗普未经证实的投票欺诈指控在佐治亚州展开调查。埃利斯的律师没有立即回复置评电话。<p></p><p>保守派人士认为，“杰夫·克拉克只是在 2020 年履行自己的职责，他不应该受到这种赤裸裸的政治法律的制裁，尤其是像威利斯这样的追名逐利者”。克拉克工作的水箱。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1F164012-9314-4C51-AF75-113013B9D8A3&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdonald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">富尔顿县地方检察官法尼·威利斯 (Fani Willis) 宣布对前总统唐纳德·特朗普 (Donald Trump) 和其他 18 人提出 41 项指控，罪名是经营一家试图推翻佐治亚州 2020 年选举的犯罪企业。照片：约翰·贝兹莫尔/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>伊士曼、梅多斯、切斯布罗和鲍威尔的律师没有立即回应置评请求。</p><p>另外三名被指控的被告是“假选举人”或“候补选举人”，这些人签署了一份证书，谎称特朗普在 2020 年选举中赢得了佐治亚州，并宣称自己是该州“正式当选且合格”的选举人。</p><p>在其他地方，政治反应按照通常的党派路线分裂。</p><p>众议院议长凯文·麦卡锡（加利福尼亚州共和党人）周一晚间在推特上指责威利斯攻击特朗普是为了推进自己的政治生涯。</p><p>众议院共和党领导层成员、纽约州众议员埃莉斯·斯特凡尼克 (Elise Stefanik) 表示：“特朗普总统拥有质疑选举结果的一切合法权利”，并指责威利斯存在偏见。</p><p>佐治亚州民主党主席、众议员尼克玛·威廉姆斯 (Nikema Williams) 表示，特朗普试图剥夺佐治亚州选民的选举权，这是对民主的攻击，因为他不喜欢 2020 年的选举结果。 “现在，唐纳德·特朗普正面临他的行为的后果，”威廉姆斯说。</p><p>起诉书还指控几名被告提交虚假文件，在某些情况下，他们发送了虚假的选举人证书，而就特朗普和伊士曼而言，他们向联邦法院提起了除夕诉讼，其中包括涉嫌的谎言，例如数千名未成年人和死者在 2020 年选举中投票。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>除 19 名被告外，起诉书还将另外 30 人描述为未起诉的同谋，因此有可能对本案提出额外指控。</p><p>民主党人威利斯的举动受到了广泛的预期。今年四月，她表示计划在今年夏天宣布指控决定，并告诉当地执法领导人为她的宣布可能引发的“重大公众反应”做好准备。</p><p>威利斯根据 2021 年 1 月 2 日的录音启动调查，当时的总统特朗普在电话中敦促佐治亚州最高选举官员、共和党人布拉德·拉芬斯佩格 (Brad Raffensperger) 找到足够的选票来推翻选举。 2024 年共和党总统提名的领跑者特朗普否认有不当行为，并表示这次通话是完美的。</p><p>威利斯召集了一个特别大陪审团，听取了超过 75 名证人的证词，撰写了一份报告，总结了调查结果，并建议对几名身份未公开的人提出刑事指控。然而，特别大陪审团无权提出起诉，这促使威利斯向常规大陪审团提供证据。</p><p> 2020 年 11 月，特朗普在佐治亚州的选举中以 500 万票中的约 12,000 票之差输给了拜登。特朗普和他的支持者声称选举被盗，但全州范围内的重新计票和州选举官员监督的部分法证审计没有发现存在普遍欺诈的证据。法庭挑战失败。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831333?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">富尔顿县地方检察官法尼·威利斯提起的起诉书称，前总统提出了选民欺诈的虚假指控，并向共和党官员施压，要求他们帮助他确保佐治亚州的选举团选票。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：布林·安德森/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周一的起诉书还概述了涉及梅多斯的多起事件，梅多斯在特朗普试图推翻 2020 年选举结果时担任白宫办公厅主任。梅多斯在联邦选举干预案中的作用微乎其微，并且无法被识别为该案中六名未起诉的同谋之一，而特朗普是该案中唯一的被告。</p><p>新的起诉书对梅多斯提出了两项​​与所谓阴谋有关的指控，称他参加了特朗普据称提出有关选举舞弊的谎言的会议，并努力安排特朗普与州官员的通话以进一步努力，其中包括特朗普询问佐治亚州的电话官员们为他寻找更多选票。</p><p>起诉书还描述了一次会议，据称特朗普和梅多斯要求特朗普助手约翰·麦肯蒂准备一份备忘录，说明如何扰乱或推迟国会 1 月 6 日的选举人票计票工作。它还指控特朗普和梅多斯试图迫使拉芬斯佩格改变公职结果，从而违反他的公职誓言。</p><p>今年早些时候，特朗普因在2016年大选前夕<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/grand-jury-votes-to-indict-donald-trump-a9512240?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">向一名色情明星支付封口费</a>而被曼哈顿地区检察官阿尔文·布拉格起诉，这是前总统首次<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/donald-trump-indictment-arrest-da-bragg?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">面临刑事指控</a>。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>针对唐纳德·特朗普的最新指控将如何展开？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>随后在 6 月，由特别检察官杰克·史密斯 (Jack Smith) 领导的联邦检察官公布了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-federal-case-against-trump-on-the-mar-a-lago-documents-12054f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一份全面的起诉书，</a>指控前总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-in-document-case-b4e563d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">持有他明知不应该保留的机密文件</a>，与其他人分享这些文件，并指示他的工作人员帮助他逃避当局的制裁。努力让他们回来。此案正在佛罗里达州处理。</p><p> 7月底返回的一份替代联邦起诉书指控特朗普另外三项罪名，其中一项是故意<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-lawyers-jack-smith-jan-6-58c2fd14?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">保留国防信息</a>，检察官称他在新泽西州的高尔夫俱乐部向访客展示了一份机密国家安全文件。</p><p> 8 月 1 日，特朗普在另一起刑事案件中第三次被起诉，指控他在 2020 年大选失败后试图通过试图保住权力来颠覆美国选民的意愿。华盛顿联邦大陪审团提出的<a href="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/documents/trumpindictment080123.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">这份起诉书</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-new-charges-facing-donald-trump-and-how-he-might-defend-himself-53a2b45?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">指控特朗普犯有四项罪行</a>，包括密谋欺骗美国、妨碍官方程序以及密谋侵犯选民的权利，最终导致 2021 年 1 月 6 日<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-protesters-are-in-the-building-inside-the-capitol-stormed-by-a-pro-trump-mob-11609984654?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的袭击他在美国国会大厦的支持者</a>。</p><p>特朗普在纽约、佛罗里达和华盛顿特区的案件中表示无罪。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/537f22eb-7442-4360-8305-39f89aae3339.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —Byron Tau、Alex Leary、Lindsay Wise 和 Isaac Yu 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Cameron McWhirter ( <a href="mailto:Cameron.McWhirter@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Cameron.McWhirter@wsj.com</a> )、Jan Wolfe ( <a href="mailto:jan.wolfe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jan.wolfe@wsj.com</a> )、Aruna Viswanatha ( <a href="mailto:aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com</a> ) 和 Sadie Gurman ( <a href="mailto:sadie.gurman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sadie.gurman@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 05:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461<author><![CDATA[Cameron McWhirterJan WolfeAruna ViswanathaSadie Gurman]]></author><category>特朗普法律</category><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>特朗普法律</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Wall Street Is Ready to Scoop Up Commercial Real Estate on the Cheap]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>公司正在筹集数十亿美元的资金，以瞄准价值下跌的资产<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833597/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="在复工步伐缓慢的情况下，写字楼市场空置率飙升。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>在复工步伐缓慢的情况下，写字楼市场空置率飙升。布伦丹·麦克德米德/路透社<span>布伦丹·麦克德米德/路透社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001133014"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001133014"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/peter-grant" itemprop="url" rel="author">彼得·格兰特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 15 日上午 12:00（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>华尔街公司正在筹集新资金来收购<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-return-to-the-office-has-stalled-e0af9741?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">办公楼</a>、公寓和其他陷入困境的商业房地产，希望以投资者几年前支付价格的一小部分收购房产。</p><p>根据监管文件<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CNS" class="">，Cohen &amp; Steers</a> <span class="company-name-type">、</span><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GS" class="">高盛</a><span class="company-name-type">、</span> EQT Exeter 和 BGO（前身为 BentallGreenOak）等知名企业筹集了数十亿美元资金，瞄准不良资产和其他价值暴跌的房地产。</p><p> “过去几周，我一直在说，‘天哪，他们是从木制品里冒出来的，’”罗伯特·A·斯坦格公司(Robert A. Stanger &amp; Co.)的首席执行官凯文·甘农(Kevin Gannon)说，该公司是一家追踪真实情况的投资银行公司。 - 遗产筹款。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">由于住房供应短缺，开发商正在将更多空置办公室改造成公寓。但并非所有建筑物都适合重复利用，尽管美国各地有超过 10 亿平方英尺的办公空间闲置 图片插图：Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>这些新基金正寻求利用数十年来最麻烦的商业地产市场之一。自去年利率飙升以来，价值急剧下降，推高了高杠杆业务的借贷成本。写字楼市场是最大的行业之一，也受到低迷的复工率的打击，导致空置率飙升。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">公寓楼</a>曾经是投资者的天堂，但随着业主试图以更高的利率进行再融资，公寓楼看起来很脆弱。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">购物中心业主正在应对</a>价值急剧下降的问题，过去几年有些跌幅超过 70%。</p><p>直到最近，商业地产销售一直停滞不前，因为大多数卖家不愿意将价格降低到买家要求的水平。现在，一小部分但数量不断增加的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rise-in-distressed-sales-signals-new-chapter-for-beleaguered-office-market-bbff313c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">写字楼业主已经开始投降</a>，出售陷入困境的房产。</p><p>这次投降标志着商业房地产剧变进入了一个新阶段，因为越来越多陷入困境的业主将房产转交给贷方或决定拿走他们能得到的东西，而不是对最终复苏抱有希望。这波融资浪潮是最新迹象，表明随着更多卖家在价格上让利，销售活动预计将增加。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="827" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834573?width=639&amp;height=827" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">开发商 Presidio Bay 以 4100 万美元的价格购买了旧金山的一座办公楼，而 2014 年的售价为 1.07 亿美元。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：杰夫·彼得斯</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>最近的一个例子是，旧金山市中心一栋办公楼的业主以 4100 万美元的价格将该房产出售给开发商 Presidio Bay。卖方 Clarion Partners 于 2014 年以 1.07 亿美元的价格购买了该房产。</p><p>虽然最明显的困境是写字楼行业，但许多拥有浮动利率债务的业主也可能感到被迫以降价出售，因为他们无法以当今较高的利率进行再融资。此外，基金经理预计，由于地区银行在今年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-collapse-crisis-timeline-724f6458?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大量银行倒闭的</a>压力下，以折扣价出售商业地产贷款组合，其价值将会下跌。</p><p>里奇·希尔 (Rich Hill) 表示：“对于能够利用弱势的投资者来说，一些选择性的机会开始出现。”</p> Cohen &amp; Steers 房地产策略主管，该公司的目标是通过新的非交易房地产投资信托筹集超过 25 亿美元。<p></p><p>希尔表示，商业地产价值已较去年第三季度的峰值下降了约 10 至 15 个百分点，并且总共可能下降 20 至 25 个百分点。 “你必须回到[储蓄和贷款]危机和全球金融危机才能看到房地产估值如此大幅下降，”他说。</p><p>数据提供商 MSCI Real Assets 的数据显示，第二季度不良商业房地产的数量增长了 80 亿美元，反映出业主违约或贷方取消抵押品赎回权的情况增加。这是自 2020 年第二季度以来的最大季度增幅。</p><p>虽然大多数新基金都打算购买房产，但也有一些基金计划向业主提供贷款，以填补地区银行和抵押房地产投资信托基金<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-lending-by-mortgage-reits-has-dried-up-49551878?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">活动减少</a>所留下的空白。由于竞争较少，仍然活跃的贷方能够收取更高的利率并从借款人那里获得更好的交易条款。</p><p>景顺房地产 (Invesco Real Estate) 拥有从机构投资者筹集房地产信贷基金资金的长期记录，目前正在筹集首个针对散户的此类基金。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>现在商业地产是否被低估？为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>许多新基金，例如 Invesco 和 Cohen &amp; Steers 筹集的基金，都是针对个人投资者的。近年来，小型投资者对房地产投资表现出了巨大的兴趣，特别是随着非交易房地产投资信托行业的增长，该行业在过去七年筹集了约 1000 亿美元。</p><p>但去年加息之前成立的许多非交易房地产投资信托基金一直面临着将资金赎回给想要套现的投资者的压力。斯坦格表示，今年前六个月已有超过 90 亿美元的资金被赎回，许多投资者因急于赎回而被迫等待领取资金。</p><p>尽管如此，新基金仍将面临来自现金充裕的机构基金的激烈竞争。数据公司 Preqin 的数据显示，私募股权公司运营的机会主义房地产基金拥有近 1,450 亿美元的所谓“干粉”用于未来投资，而去年底这一数字为 1,200 亿美元。</p><p>如果美国经济实现<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-top-executives-are-saying-about-a-soft-landing-4daf9123?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">软着陆</a>，即美联储抑制通胀而不导致经济陷入衰退，那么困境机会仍有可能不会出现。</p><p>当债务市场稳定且价值变得更加清晰时，销量可能会增加。全球咨询公司兼配售代理 PJT Park Hill 房地产集团联席主管迈克尔·斯塔克 (Michael Stark) 表示：“从广义上讲，人们都在等着看世界是什么样子。” “他们正在等待积极主动的卖家。”</p><p>写信给彼得·格兰特： <a href="mailto:peter.grant@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">peter.grant@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f<author><![CDATA[Peter Grant]]></author><category>商业地产</category><category>海运</category><category>信托/基金/金融工具</category><category>投资信托</category><category>房地产投资信托</category><category>房地产服务/交易</category><category>货运/物流</category><category>商业/工业地产</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>海运</category><category>房地产</category><category>水路运输/航运</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>实物资产交易</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>商业房地产</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>科恩和斯蒂尔斯</category><category>中枢神经系统</category><category>高盛</category><category>GS</category><category>殷拓埃克塞特</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>实物资产交易</category><category>企业行动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>海运</category><category>信托</category><category>资金</category><category>金融工具</category><category>投资信托</category><category>房地产投资信托</category><category>房地产服务</category><category>交易</category><category>货运</category><category>后勤</category><category>商业的</category><category>工业地产</category><category>房地产</category><category>建造</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category><category>海运</category><category>水运</category><category>船运</category><category>运输</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Artist’s Mother: Whistler and Philadelphia’ Review: Mismatched Maternal Portraits]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>费城艺术博物馆的一次展览试图将惠斯勒的母亲画作与类似主题的作品进行对话，包括爱丽丝·尼尔、约翰·斯隆等人的作品。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590142681126749908"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="763" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835239?width=860&amp;height=763" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">詹姆斯·阿伯特·麦克尼尔·惠斯勒《灰黑编曲 No. 1》（1871 年）</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：RMN-大皇宫</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590142681126749908"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">兰斯·埃斯普伦德</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日晚上 7:19 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-artists-mother-whistler-and-philadelphia-review-mismatched-maternal-portraits-20e202af"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><em>费城</em></p><p>埃兹拉·庞德<strong>在 1911 年的诗</strong>《致惠斯勒，美国人》中称詹姆斯·阿伯特·麦克尼尔·惠斯勒是“我们第一位伟大的”美国人，他的一些艺术作品“像丢勒一样完美！”庞德所指的“完美”照片之一是惠斯勒那幅充满心理色彩的真人大小肖像画《灰黑排列第一号》(1871)。它通常被称为“惠斯勒的母亲”，它是“艺术家的母亲：惠斯勒和费城”的指南针，这是费城艺术博物馆举办的一场平易近人但参差不齐的展览，展出了四幅画作和五幅纸上作品。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p><strong>艺术家的母亲：惠斯勒和费城</strong></p><p><em>费城艺术博物馆<br>截至 10 月 29 日</em></p></div></div><p>1881 年，《灰黑编排第一号》在美国宾夕法尼亚美术学院首次展出，这是惠斯勒（居住在伦敦）的画作第二次在美国展出。由 PMA 的詹妮弗·汤普森 (Jennifer Thompson) 策划的“惠斯勒与费城”欢迎现藏于巴黎奥赛博物馆的“惠斯勒母亲”142 年来首次回到这座城市。该节目的前提——艺术家（孩子）和主题（母亲）——很简单。将惠斯勒的肖像与 19 世纪和 20 世纪与兄弟（和母爱）之城相关的美国艺术家的母亲肖像进行对话。</p><p>惠斯勒（1834-1903 年）出生于马萨诸塞州洛厄尔，居住在马里兰州康涅狄格州和西点军校，他的父亲在那里教授绘画，罗伯特·E·李上校因记过过多而解雇了这名学员。惠斯勒还居住在俄罗斯圣彼得堡（他的父亲在那里为沙皇尼古拉斯一世设计了一条铁路）；在巴黎（他在那里结识了诗人波德莱尔、现实主义者库尔贝以及印象派马奈、德加和莫奈）； 1859 年，他在伦敦定居。</p><p> 《灰与黑的安排第一号》描绘了 67 岁的安娜·玛蒂尔达·麦克尼尔·惠斯勒，她在儿子的要求下更换了伦敦工作室中一位生病的模特。惠斯勒的画作是一曲由抛光青铜、银色、棕色、白色和黑色组成的引人注目的交响乐，介于荷兰黄金时代忧郁的室内装饰和结构严谨、棱角分明的 20 世纪抽象画之间。在这里，严肃的安娜侧身坐着，两眼直视前方，仿佛看到了一个不祥的未来。她是一个巨大的、不可逾越的群体——有时是虚无的——黑暗。她的膝盖很大。她的头、手和脚似乎是分离的，就像漆黑大海中的群岛。她的腿不成比例地拉长，像蜘蛛一样伸展。虽然停泊，但她仍在运动。而且房间在不断变化。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="520" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835260?width=700&amp;height=520" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">亨利·奥萨瓦·坦纳 (Henry Ossawa Tanner) 的《艺术家母亲的肖像》(1897)</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：费城艺术博物馆</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>安娜摇摇欲坠地坐着，好像抱着一个壁架。有些地方地板倾斜或溶解，表明她可以直接从画中滑出。在其他照片中，她的身体向后倾斜，穿透墙壁——现在是雾气。其中最突出的形式是两幅悬挂的白色画，其中可以说是惠斯勒的蚀刻版画《黑狮码头》（1859 年），它位于惠斯勒画作的中心，在 PMA 中安装在附近。这两个平坦、明亮的矩形向前延伸至构图的前平面，与惠斯勒的母亲竞争，后者笔直向前，就像一艘满载的驳船穿过冰原。</p><p>与列奥纳多的《蒙娜丽莎》一样，《灰黑排列一号》（越来越多地被称为“维多利亚时代的蒙娜丽莎”）是一幅画家和画中人不可分割地融合在一起的肖像画。它已成为坚定母性和清教徒理想的化身。但不总是。惠斯勒的肖像画于 1872 年在伦敦皇家艺术学院首次亮相。几乎被英国皇家学会拒绝，部分原因是其抽象的标题，它被嘲笑和嘲笑为过于坚忍和严肃——坚决反维多利亚时代。惠斯勒最终典当了这幅画，并于 1891 年被法国政府收购。</p><p> 《惠斯勒与费城》将《灰与黑的安排第一》与塞西莉亚·博克斯、亨利·奥萨瓦·坦纳、约翰·斯隆、多克斯·思拉什、爱丽丝·尼尔和西德尼·古德曼的肖像作品进行了正面交锋。古德曼的大幅画作《艺术家的母亲 I》（1994）引人注目，画中弗朗西斯似乎从床上爬起来，就像从坟墓里爬起来一样。同样值得注意的是，弗朗切斯科·诺维利 (Francesco Novelli) 于 1792 年根据伦勃朗蚀刻版画《坐在东方头饰中的艺术家的母亲：半身》(1631) 创作的复制品，惠斯勒可能对此很熟悉；费城人斯隆的热情致敬作品《母亲》（1906 年）是亨丽埃塔的蚀刻画，坐着，抱着她的狗迪克西。尼尔的《最后的疾病》（Last Sickness，1953）是艺术家为她年迈的母亲绘制的油画肖像——穿着格子长袍，戴着歪斜的眼镜，斜视着——美丽而哀伤，涩涩。这是这里最值得与惠斯勒分享墙壁空间的肖像。但即使它也不真正属于。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="875" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835259?width=639&amp;height=875" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">艾丽丝·尼尔的《最后的疾病》(1953)</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：费城艺术博物馆</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>惠斯勒是一位虔诚的形式主义者和雄辩的理论家，他倡导“为艺术而艺术”。他认为真正的艺术是通过线条、色彩和节奏（即形式）的和谐来表达的，并具有完全不受社会、政治或道德功能（即题材）影响的独立生命。惠斯勒将他的画作展示为“灰色和黑色的排列”，因为他说，“现在就是这样。”他将观众的注意力集中在其动态构图上，而不是其艺术作品的主题上。 《惠斯勒和费城》的灵感来自惠斯勒的母亲，而不是他的艺术，与惠斯勒所代表的一切背道而驰。</p><p> 《灰与黑的排列1》与蒙德里安的抽象画或布拉克的灰色立体派肖像画有更多的共同点，而不是坦纳和博克斯感伤的惠斯勒模仿作品。庞德将惠斯勒比作亚伯·林肯，不需要庞德就知道哪张照片比其他照片更出色。众所周知，6 岁的孩子就能告诉你。当我在 PMA 时，我看到惠斯勒的标志性肖像，并要求：“让我们看看那位女士！”不幸的是，他的父亲把他带到了邻近的画廊。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。埃斯普伦德是《观看的艺术：如何阅读现当代艺术》（基础书籍）一书的作者，为该杂志撰写有关艺术的文章。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 23:19:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-artists-mother-whistler-and-philadelphia-review-mismatched-maternal-portraits-20e202af</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-artists-mother-whistler-and-philadelphia-review-mismatched-maternal-portraits-20e202af<category>艺术评论</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Partition Voices’ Review: Free of Empire But Not Strife]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着印度的独立，大规模移民和前邻国之间发生了可怕的暴力事件。还有勇敢和善良的行为。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140611795335380"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835235?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴基斯坦卡拉奇附近的穆斯林难民等待搬入住房。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Keystone-France/Gamma-Keystone 来自 Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140611795335380"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">东姑·瓦拉达拉詹</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日下午 6:21 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/partition-voices-review-free-of-empire-but-not-strife-8cc4f09f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>新的穆斯林国家巴基斯坦与印度教徒占多数的印度分离二十年后，奥登发表了一首刻薄的小诗，题为《分治》。这是 1947 年 8 月给殖民地印度的分裂贴上的标签（总是大写）。数以百万计的人都采用了这个标签，他们的生活因这次宗派重组的创伤而被重塑或摧毁，也被签署该项目的英国执政党</p><p><em>隔断一词</em>通常用于描述住宅内的分隔。这种家庭分裂的感觉仍然充满着理解这一构造事件的尝试。 Auden wrote of how Cyril Radcliffe—the British barrister who had “never set eyes on this land he was called to partition”—had been assigned the task of separating “two peoples fanatically at odds, / With their different diets and incompatible gods.” It&#39;s a jaunty line, a little dated in its Orientalism, but it encapsulates the deep-rooted differences—between Muslims, on the one hand, and Hindus and Sikhs, on the other—that were to find bloodthirsty expression in the course of Partition. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/6a39833b-310f-4751-bf62-c66639054a92.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Lord Mountbatten, the last viceroy of the Raj, was keen to go down in history as the sainted man on whose watch India attained its freedom. And so he brought forward the calendar of independence, moving the official date from June 1948 to August 1947. Mountbatten&#39;s haste—arguably self-serving and reckless—left poor Radcliffe the map- <em>wallah</em> a mere five weeks to complete a task of such magnitude that five years might have been insufficient. The fates of millions depended on the stroke of his technocratic pen, which changed not just the map he scored with brand-new borders but also the world&#39;s geopolitics; 75 years later, peoples who were once all Indian constitute two hostile, nuclear-armed nations.</p><p> There is no mention of Auden in “Partition Voices,” by Kavita Puri, but his absence detracts in no way from the eloquence of a book based on the oral testimonies of those who lived through the largest peacetime migrations in history. The word peacetime, here, denotes the fact that newly independent India and fledgling Pakistan were not officially at war. But in every other respect, the migrations were in response to violence—actual, threatened or anticipated.</p><p> A million lives were lost, the majority to religion-fueled murder. Ms. Puri writes that 75,000 women were raped by men from religions other than their own. Fathers were known to kill their own daughters to save them from “dishonor” at the hands of mobs. Fifteen million people crossed the borders of Punjab, in western India, and Bengal in the east. Both provinces—the most strategically significant in British India—were cleft in two.</p><p> Muslims were ethnically cleansed from east Punjab, which was assigned to India. They migrated in trains or on foot to their new country of Pakistan. Hindus and Sikhs were cleansed from west Punjab (now Pakistan), fleeing east to India across a border that had not existed before. There was, by contrast, a much smaller shifting of populations in Bengal—along India&#39;s border with Burma—and much less of the frenzy that beset the Punjabis. Bengal had already been partitioned once, in 1905, so it coped better with the psychic blow in 1947. (In 1971, the map of Bengal would be redrawn once more, with the bloody emergence of Bangladesh.)</p><p> Fears were magnified by the astonishing fact that when Pakistan became independent on Aug. 14, 1947, and India on Aug. 15, millions of people in Punjab and Bengal didn&#39;t know on which side of the border their homes would fall. They would find out later, Ms. Puri tells us, from the radio or from the religious identity of the mobs that converged on their villages.</p><p> Many families in villages that hugged the impending border took the precaution of packing in advance. Houses, cattle and keys were entrusted to neighbors who were of the religion that fit the new reality. Many who became refugees refused to believe that they would not return when the madness had abated. But their neighbors were themselves caught up in the bloodlust, killing—or driving out from their homes—people with whom they&#39;d lived for generations, simply because the targets were Sikh in a village now turned Muslim or Muslim in a hamlet that had become Hindu.</p><p> Ms. Puri is a British journalist of Punjabi Hindu origins whose father was from Lahore, now in Pakistan. She was born in Britain, to which her parents migrated like thousands of others from the Indian subcontinent—a majority from the partitioned provinces. Her book—first published in 2019 and updated last year to mark the 75th year of Partition—is based on interviews she conducted with British Sikhs, Hindus and Muslims, as well as a few white Britons, for a series that aired on Britain&#39;s Radio 4 in 2017. “Untold British Stories,” the subtitle of “Partition Voices,” reflects the fact that the tales of her interlocutors are a part of British history. As such, she insists, they must be taught in British schools.</p><p> Many of the people she interviewed are now dead, and those who survive are touching 90. Their stories are harrowing, recounting how fathers were slain, sisters abducted, homes burned and lives shattered. But there are also accounts of bravery and kindness—of Muslims who sheltered Hindus from attack, of Sikh men who saved Muslim women from rape. A Muslim neighbor could be your murderer or savior. A gentle Sikh farmer could join a gang that went in search of Muslims to kill or help you hide in his cattle shed. Time and again Ms. Puri confronts the vexing question: “How was it possible for people who once coexisted peacefully together to murder each other, and so viciously?”</p><p> Such questions were asked after the Holocaust and other episodes of genocide (in the Balkans in the 1990s, for instance, or in Rwanda). In the case of Partition, there has long been a veil of silence. Thanks to Ms. Puri and others, that silence is giving way to inquisitive—and assertive—voices. In Britain, at least, the partitioned have learned to speak frankly of the past—and to search for ways to reckon with it.</p><p> <em>Mr. Varadarajan, a Journal contributor, is a fellow at the American Enterprise Institute and at NYU Law School&#39;s Classical Liberal Institute.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 22:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/partition-voices-review-free-of-empire-but-not-strife-8cc4f09f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/partition-voices-review-free-of-empire-but-not-strife-8cc4f09f<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Ash’ by Mat Maneri Quartet Review: Jazz That Treasures the In-Between]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The violist and his band continue to defy easy categorization as they draw from their varied pasts and mesh genres from classical to Eastern European folk, producing novel results. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590140593096289882"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834395?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mat Maneri</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Antonio Porcar </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590140593096289882"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Larry Blumenfeld</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 14, 2023 5:32 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ash-by-mat-maneri-quartet-review-jazz-sunnyside-4b9176f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><strong></strong></p><p> The pages of MAD magazine have long included “marginals” by artist Sergio Aragonés —tiny line drawings that creep from the edges of pages. They appear as if coming from nowhere yet communicate a great deal, wordlessly.</p><p> Violist Mat Maneri&#39;s music is a bit like those drawings. These purely instrumental songs—mostly original compositions and adaptations, often of Eastern European folk music or Western classical repertoire—seem to drift in from someplace just out of view, their gestural strokes and shifting colors more so than any particular notes conveying meaning. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834380?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><p> Such is the case with the first and title track of “Ash” (Sunnyside), the new release from Mr. Maneri&#39;s quartet. It begins with broad, slightly warped tones bowed by Mr. Maneri. The feeling is spacious, the development much like stasis just beginning to yield to motion. Pianist Lucian Ban plays spare figures and isolated chords. The sound of John Hébert&#39;s bass arrives like enveloping thuds. Drummer Randy Peterson&#39;s snare-drum rattles and light cymbal strikes color the air more than move any beat. Yet halfway in there&#39;s a gentle propulsion and collective impression: Mr. Maneri&#39;s tones grow purer, more direct. His quartet&#39;s interplay sounds less like a new song forming than the remnants of an old one being recovered.</p><p> If this music emanates from anywhere, it is from mists of the past. Mr. Maneri&#39;s compositions here “delve into deep-rooted memories,” he told me, “that maybe have been distorted over time.” Most of these memories, as far as music is concerned, connect to his father, Joe Maneri —an innovative saxophonist, clarinetist and composer who was an influential teacher at the New England Conservatory in Boston for 37 years, and who died in 2009. Regular soirées at the Maneri household when Mat was a boy would involve Joe&#39;s colleagues, such as the composer and historian Gunther Schuller, as well as Joe&#39;s many students.</p><p> Mat&#39;s deepest memories are buried within particular musical phrases or renditions. One track here, “Brahms,” is based on the Andante from Johannes Brahms&#39;s Viola Sonata No. 1, Op. 120, as Mr. Maneri remembers it played by violist James Bergin, who studied with his father. The brief yet dramatic phrases that form the basis of Mr. Maneri&#39;s “Earth” were drawn from a 1964 “Peace Concert” by his father (in duet with drummer Peter Dolger ), which Mr. Maneri listened to obsessively on a reel-to-reel tape (it was commercially released in 2008).</p><p> Mr. Maneri is one of modern music&#39;s most distinctive string players, and one of its freest-ranging talents. He has played with past masters including pianists Cecil Taylor and Paul Bley, and is an essential element in several important groups (pianist Matthew Shipp&#39;s String Trio, including Mr. Maneri and bassist William Parker, is a singular and wondrous ensemble).</p><p> If his playing knows no genre and often defies standard notation, it&#39;s because he was raised in the spaces between those styles and notes. Joe Maneri&#39;s music and scholarship placed modern jazz, composer Arnold Schoenberg&#39;s Second Viennese School, and Eastern European folk styles on equal footing; his abiding fascination was with microtonalism, music that uses intervals smaller than the semitone, the smallest by Western music standards (and which occur naturally in most folk music and blues). The quartet Mat played in and assembled in the 1990s for his father to lead focused on, he told me, “pitches within pitches, rhythms within rhythms, dynamics within dynamics.”</p><p> That same sense of granular expression, of continuums rather than fixed points, animates Mr. Maneri&#39;s current quartet, which made its debut on his 2019 release, “Dust.” These musicians now mine their own communal memories. Mr. Maneri began playing with Mr. Peterson in the 1980s and with Mr. Hébert a decade later. His close bond with Mr. Ban, who was born and raised in central Romania, began in 2010, and includes their 2013 duet recording, “Transylvanian Concert.”</p><p> On the new release Mr. Ban&#39;s composition “Dust to Dust” extends his “Mojave,” from Mr. Maneri&#39;s previous recording, into a 10-minute-plus piece; Mr. Maneri plays its bittersweet melody with brilliant clarity and complex shades of feeling. For his own composition “Cold World Lullaby,” Mr. Maneri draws upon three references: Sol Kaplan&#39;s score to “The Spy Who Came in From the Cold” (a favorite film of his childhood); a Sicilian lullaby his grandfather taught him; and “Lume, Lume,” a traditional Romanian song he learned from Mr. Ban. On another original composition, “Glimmer,” Mr. Maneri&#39;s viola often sounds like a horn in a jazz band—a quality that he said owes as much to his studies of Baroque music with Juilliard String Quartet co-founder Robert Koff as to his listening to Miles Davis recordings. It also results from the way he combines his instrument&#39;s natural qualities with deft use of amplification and a volume pedal.</p><p> In Mr. Maneri&#39;s hands, the viola is both acoustic and electric; each tone is neither this note nor that; his quartet, which sometimes sounds larger than it is, mostly moves as one; and his music speaks simultaneously of a distant past and a present moment.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Blumenfeld writes about jazz and Afro-Latin music for the Journal and is editorial director for Chamber Music America.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 21:32:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ash-by-mat-maneri-quartet-review-jazz-sunnyside-4b9176f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ash-by-mat-maneri-quartet-review-jazz-sunnyside-4b9176f<category> arts in review</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Death of Public School’ Review: Find a Place to Learn]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>从比尔·克林顿到巴拉克·奥巴马，民主党人都支持特许学校和学校选择，直到教师工会威胁终止他们的支持。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11551743921986544093504589603082880894504"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834832?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2022 年，新墨西哥州阿尔伯克基使命成就与成功特许学校的三年级学生。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿尔伯克基日报/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11551743921986544093504589603082880894504"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">内奥米·谢弗·莱利</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 13 日下午 3:18 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-death-of-public-school-review-find-a-place-to-learn-4817d47c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>什么是公立学校？它是一个由公众付费的机构吗？一名由政府雇员组成的人员？一个教授公开认可的课程的学校？一个能够教育广大公众儿童的学校？在《公立学校之死》一书的作者卡拉·菲茨帕特里克看来，它具备所有这些品质，而且确实如此。不少家长不同意，或者对公立学校的想法完全不再抱有希望，这让她感到担忧。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a74aaa7c-35f1-4344-b5a3-aafc1dd7194d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>菲茨帕特里克女士是一名资深记者，也是教育网站 Chalkbeat 的编辑，对于她来说，公立学校的消亡——或者至少是衰落——主要归因于保守派，正如她的副标题所言，他们“赢得了教育领域的战争”。美国。”在她看来，他们通过支持择校、学校券和特许学校来推进他们的进攻。</p><p>菲茨帕特里克女士对这些另类政策和制度的不太同情的历史始于 20 世纪 50 年代的种族隔离主义者。 She shows how the people who opposed racial integration in the civil-rights era lined up behind the idea that parents should get to choose their children&#39;s school—with the goal, in that era, of avoiding black children.她指出，在<em>布朗诉教育委员会案</em>（1954 年最高法院裁决废除学校种族隔离）的四年内，一些南方州“在必要时采取措施放弃公立学校”，并“设立了助学金，供学生用来支付私立学校的学费”。学校。”菲茨帕特里克女士表示，此类举措是“创建学校学券制度的第一步”，类似于米尔顿·弗里德曼 (Milton Friedman) 在 1955 年特别提出的制度。</p><p>尽管菲茨帕特里克女士并没有指责弗里德曼与南方人有相同的动机——她引用了他的话说，他鄙视种族隔离和种族偏见——但她说，他对代金券的看法似乎“要么天真，要么故意无视南方的种族压迫”。 ”。 Friedman had argued that a private system—with vouchers helping families pay for tuition—would offer a range of voluntary associations: exclusively white, exclusively black and mixed schools. Rather than force parents to send their children to one kind or another, he said, people opposed to racial prejudice should “try to persuade others of their views.”如果他们成功了，“混合学校的发展将以牺牲非混合学校为代价，并且逐步过渡将会发生。”</p><p>很难说这样的想法是否幼稚。 it certainly wasn&#39;t ignorant or baleful, as Mr. Fitzpatrick seems to imply. At the time, there were high-quality institutions devoted exclusively to black students, notably the Rosenwald schools set up in the South by the philanthropist Julius Rosenwald in the first decades of the 20th century. If black parents had been given the vouchers needed to support them, such schools might well have continued to flourish.</p><p>当然，人们支持择校的原因不止一个。 Some have favored limited government, feeling that, when it comes to the education of children, the state should yield to the preferences of parents. Some have favored more resources for religious schools. Virgil Blum, a Jesuit professor at Marquette University, wrote an article in the late 1950s calling for “educational benefits without enforced conformity,” by which he meant that children shouldn&#39;t be denied access to either public or private schools for lack of funds.在某种程度上，他想让天主教学校系统成为公立学校的更强大的替代品，公立学校有时是由不容忍宗教异见的新教徒开办的。</p><p>学校选择或学券——或者特许学校（特许学校在政府限制和教师工会规则之外运作，同时接受公共资金）所带来的教育有多好？ Ms. Fitzpatrick says that the jury is still out. She cites various studies, with mixed conclusions.她没有提到就读 Success Academy 的学生考试成绩得到了天文数字般的提高。 Success Academy 是纽约市特许学校网络，成立于 2006 年，目前为 20,000 多名 K-12 年级的学生提供服务。</p><p>关于教育的争论可能会造成奇怪的同床异梦。 Ms. Fitzpatrick tells the story of the alliance in the 1990s between the Milwaukee-based black Democratic legislator Polly Williams, who favored private-school vouchers, and Wisconsin&#39;s white Republican Gov. Tommy Thompson. After helping to implement the country&#39;s first voucher program, Williams turned on Thompson because he wanted vouchers to be universal and she wanted them to go only to the poor.</p><p>菲茨帕特里克女士似乎觉得，倾向民主党的黑人家长正在被倾向共和党的白人倡导者玩弄，他们推动公立学校的替代方案。 Such advocates say they care about the best interests of inner-city children—whose public schools are often miserable—but Ms. Fitzpatrick implies that they really want to engage in religious indoctrination (with church-defined curriculums) or to make money by ultimately privatizing public schools.她毫不客气地形容克林特·博利克（Clint Bolick）——他是许多第一批学券案件的辩护人——“永远不会错过一个良好的公共关系机会”。</p><p>对于那些似乎倾向于质疑那些支持择校的人的动机的人来说，菲茨帕特里克女士似乎对其他人反对的原因不太感兴趣。从比尔·克林顿到巴拉克·奥巴马等民主党人最初支持特许学校和学校选择，但当教师工会威胁撤回他们的政治支持时，他们就放弃了。</p><p>那么，遗憾的是，除了引言中的几句话外，菲茨帕特里克女士的分析到了 2019 年就结束了。2020-21 年的大流行向来自不同地理区域和政治背景的家长暴露了公立学校的缺陷。效忠，尤其是当老师不听话，导致孩子们无法上学并导致他们落后时。 At least five states have passed universal school choice in the past two years. If Ms. Fitzpatrick thought public schools were dead before, wait until she sees what happens next.</p><p><em>莱利女士是美国企业研究所的高级研究员。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 13 Aug 2023 19:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-death-of-public-school-review-find-a-place-to-learn-4817d47c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-death-of-public-school-review-find-a-place-to-learn-4817d47c<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>种族主义/仇外心理</category><category>学校</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>种族主义</category><category>仇外心理</category><category>学校</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item></channel></rss>